  "description": "Most [linear maps](./linear-map.md) scramble directions — they stretch space one way, compress it another, and rotate things sideways. But along certain special directions, a linear map does something simple: it just scales. An eigenvalue is the scaling factor along one of these special directions, and the direction itself is called an eigenvector.",
